This transforms the inequality into \( |u - 1| + |v - 1| \le 1 \), where \( u \) and \( v \) are non-negative. 1. **Case Analysis in the \( uv \)-plane**: - **Case 1**: \( u \ge 1 \) and \( v \ge 1 \). The inequality simplifies to \( u + v \le 3 \). - **Case 2**: \( u \ge 1 \) and \( v < 1 \). The inequality simplifies to \( u - v \le 1 \). - **Case 3**: \( u < 1 \) and \( v \ge 1 \). The inequality simplifies to \( v - u \le 1 \). - **Case 4**: \( u < 1 \) and \( v < 1 \). The inequality simplifies to \( u + v \ge 1 \). 2. **Area Calculation in the \( uv \)-plane**: - Each case contributes to a region in the first quadrant of the \( uv \)-plane. - The total area in the first quadrant is calculated as 0.5 for each of the four cases, summing to 2. - Since the problem is symmetric across all four quadrants, the total area in the \( uv \)-plane is \( 4 \times 2 = 8 \). 3. **Mapping Back to the \( xy \)-plane**: - Each point \( (u, v) \) in the \( uv \)-plane corresponds to four points \( (\pm u, \pm v) \) in the \( xy \)-plane. - Therefore, the area in the \( xy \)-plane is four times the area in the \( uv \)-plane, resulting in \( 4 \times 2 = 8 \). Thus, the area of the region defined by \( ||x| - 1| + ||y| - 1| \le 1 \) is \(\boxed{8}\).
